00:20:06.650 --> 00:20:12.870
The, what really surprised me
was that in [foreign language]

00:20:12.870 --> 00:20:18.520
of the attachment to
the Amstsblatt itself,

00:20:18.520 --> 00:20:23.030
in the early years one
frequently found out in Hebrew.

00:20:23.030 --> 00:20:29.060
Because there was no other
place of general availability

00:20:29.060 --> 00:20:33.020
of this kind of information.

00:20:33.020 --> 00:20:40.010
That did not continue
once there were newspapers

00:20:40.010 --> 00:20:44.000
of general circulation
in the Province.

00:20:51.380 --> 00:20:59.200
Next, there were, I discussed
German archival holdings.

00:20:59.200 --> 00:21:09.670 position:56%
That's a difficult problem in a way,
because on the 29th of January 1945,

00:21:09.670 --> 00:21:19.070
the retreating German army set fire
to the then Pol's and archives.

00:21:19.070 --> 00:21:24.140
Burning everything that was in it
except for 80 chests of documents

00:21:24.140 --> 00:21:29.600
which were taken away and we
don't know what happened to those.

00:21:29.600 --> 00:21:34.310
Perhaps they're in some salt
mine or something like that.

00:21:34.310 --> 00:21:37.250
We don't know.

00:21:37.250 --> 00:21:40.310
You would think that they probably
would have been found by now,

00:21:40.310 --> 00:21:44.810
if they were going to be found.

00:21:44.810 --> 00:21:46.610
It's a great loss.

00:21:46.610 --> 00:21:56.430
But in 1919 a German Jewish
archivist inventoried the entire

00:21:56.430 --> 00:22:02.050
collection and published
it and I have reproduced

00:22:02.050 --> 00:22:08.920
in my book the listing
of what was destroyed.

00:22:08.920 --> 00:22:13.150
So at least we know what
doesn't exist anymore

00:22:13.150 --> 00:22:17.010
or if it does exist,
has not been found.

00:22:17.010 --> 00:22:23.290
A great shame but the, not
everything was in that archives

00:22:23.290 --> 00:22:27.430
and so other things
that did survive are now

00:22:27.430 --> 00:22:31.470
in the current archives in Poznan.

00:22:31.470 --> 00:22:36.270
And are available for
legitimate researchers.

00:22:36.270 --> 00:22:43.720
It's amazing what they did manage
to collect and I had lunch once

00:22:43.720 --> 00:22:51.170
with one archival curator
and told me,

00:22:51.170 --> 00:22:54.960
he told me just the
previous week he came

00:22:54.960 --> 00:23:02.360
across valuable documents hidden
from the Nazi's in a barn.

00:23:02.360 --> 00:23:09.610
And only discovered long after the
death of whoever hid those items.

00:23:09.610 --> 00:23:13.430
So things are sometimes
still being discovered.

00:23:13.430 --> 00:23:17.760
It's getting rarer and
rarer but it is happening

00:23:17.760 --> 00:23:22.100
and the Pol's have
made a determination

00:23:22.100 --> 00:23:25.090
that they will pretty
much put older,

00:23:25.090 --> 00:23:28.870
older archival documents
online eventually,

00:23:28.870 --> 00:23:32.020
but it's such a large collection

00:23:32.020 --> 00:23:38.620
that it will take many many
years before they finish.

00:23:38.620 --> 00:23:51.220
